2026-05-02 | Maximum Sum Pair With Difference Less Than K

	Question
Return the maximum possible pair sum.
	Key Insight
After sorting:
		a[0] ≤ a[1] ≤ ... ≤ a[n-1]
If:
		a[i] - a[i-1] < k
then pairing these two adjacent elements is always the best choice.
Why?
Because a[i] is the largest remaining element.
If it can form a valid pair with a[i-1],
pairing it with any earlier element would only reduce the sum.
This leads to DP.
	Approach
1.	Sort the array.
2.	Define:
		dp[i]
		= maximum sum obtainable using first i elements.
3.	Transition:
		If arr[i] - arr[i-1] < k
		then either:
		- don't use arr[i]
				dp[i-1]
		- pair arr[i] with arr[i-1]
				dp[i-2] + arr[i] + arr[i-1]
		Take maximum.
4.	If pair not possible:
		dp[i] = dp[i-1]
5.	Return dp[n-1].
	Time Complexity
	O(n log n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int maxSumPairWithDifferenceLessThanK(vector<int>& arr, int k) {
        int n = arr.size();
        sort(arr.begin(), arr.end());
        vector<int> dp(n, 0);
        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            dp[i] = dp[i - 1];
            if(arr[i] - arr[i - 1] < k) {
                int pairSum = arr[i] + arr[i - 1];
                if(i >= 2)
                    pairSum += dp[i - 2];
                dp[i] = max(dp[i], pairSum);
            }
        }
        return dp[n - 1];
    }
};
	Key Insight
After sorting, whenever two adjacent elements can form a valid pair, they are the most profitable pair involving the larger element. Dynamic Programming then decides whether taking that pair produces a better total sum than skipping it.
